  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Misunderstanding the AED 2M Equity Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The AED 2 million threshold refers to your equity, not the property price. If you buy a AED 4 million property with 50% mortgage, your equity is AED 2 million—barely qualifying. Many applicants mistakenly assume the purchase price is what matters. With a mortgage, ensure your equity portion meets the threshold.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Proper Health Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Health insurance is mandatory and strictly enforced. Some applicants try to use travel insurance or non-compliant policies—these will be rejected. Get proper DHA/DOH-compliant coverage before applying. Budget $3,000-8,000/year for quality coverage and factor this into your ongoing costs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Inadequate Source of Funds Documentation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The UAE requires proof of legitimate fund sources. Investors who cannot clearly document how they accumulated their investment capital face delays or rejections. Prepare bank statements, business records, asset sale documentation, or inheritance records. Cryptocurrency gains require particularly detailed documentation.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Neglecting Emirates ID After Visa Approval</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Some investors complete the visa stamp but delay getting their Emirates ID. This creates problems—you need the Emirates ID for banking, phone contracts, hotel stays, and most daily activities. Complete the Emirates ID application immediately after visa approval, not weeks later.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Assuming No Ongoing Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While there's no minimum stay requirement, you must maintain your investment and valid health insurance throughout the 10-year period. Selling your property means losing your visa. Letting insurance lapse creates problems at renewal. Plan for ongoing costs and commitments, not just initial setup.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

